ODE IV.

The first ode in this book was composed in honor of Augustus, and in the hope that he would return immediately. This was written in consequence of his delay3 and is an expression of the affection of the Romans for Augustus, and of their impatience for ln's return. The other was animated with Pindaric fire, and seem- ed to be an eamest of the triumph that awaited Augustus 3 while this is full of tenderness and desire for his return.
